{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_10","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/prompt.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Implement `ralph-burning` v1 Rewrite\n\n## 1) Objective and Source of Truth\nYou are implementing a greenfield Rust rewrite of the orchestrator in `ralph-burning-rewrite/`. The existing code in `multibackend-orchestration/` is **read-only reference-only** for behavior inference; do not preserve or migrate legacy `.ralph` state, artifact formats, loop directories, or git checkpoint encoding.\n\n## 2) Product Definition\nBuild a modular monolith called `ralph-burning` with one binary and these hard constraints:\n- Rust implementation.\n- New workspace root is `.ralph-burning/`.\n- Built-in flow presets are exactly: `standard`, `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, `ci_improvement`.\n- No arbitrary user-defined flow DSL in v1.\n- Markdown is only a rendered, human-readable artifact, not workflow protocol.\n- Canonical workflow state is structured stage payload JSON + run state + journal.\n- Runtime logs are ephemeral and never part of durable project history.\n\n## 3) Non-goals\n- No compatibility layer for old `.ralph` workspaces or legacy reconstruction logic.\n- No service-oriented microservice split in v1.\n- No full implementation of every slice before completing core canonical state and shared engine.\n\n## 4) Canonical Vocabulary (must use consistently)\n- `workspace`: orchestration root `.ralph-burning/`\n- `project`: durable work item with immutable `flow`\n- `run`: execution instance for a project\n- `stage`: named step in a flow preset\n- `stage cursor`: current stage + cycle + attempt metadata\n- `work cycle`: unit of iterative delivery work\n- `completion round`: unit deciding complete vs continue\n- `backend family`: e.g., Claude, Codex, OpenRouter\n- `stage contract`: schema + required fields + semantic validation rules\n- `stage payload`: validated structured output\n- `history artifact`: rendered Markdown derived from payload\n- `runtime log`: operational/debug output\n- `journal`: append-only domain event log\n- `rollback point`: durable logical checkpoint\n- `task`: daemon unit of automated work\n\nDecision in this prompt:\n- Use canonical term `cycle` in public docs and CLI; accept `loop` as deprecated alias only for informational output, not as a primary API term.\n\n## 5) Bounded Contexts (required)\nImplement the following context packages with ports/adapters boundaries:\n\n- `contexts/workspace_governance/*`\n- `contexts/project_run_record/*`\n- `contexts/workflow_composition/*`\n- `contexts/agent_execution/*`\n- `contexts/requirements_drafting/*`\n- `contexts/automation_runtime/*`\n- `contexts/conformance_spec/*`\n- `adapters/*` for side effects\n\nPrimary dependencies:\n- `workspace_governance` is upstream for config and flow discovery.\n- `project_run_record` is source of durable truth.\n- `workflow_composition` drives run progression.\n- `agent_execution` provides invocation + normalized structured results.\n- `automation_runtime` consumes routing and dispatches into workflow/requirements.\n\n## 6) Folder and Storage Layout\nUse this model in `ralph-burning-rewrite/`:\n\n`src/`\n- `main.rs`\n- composition, shared, contexts, adapters, etc. as per provided package sketch.\n\n`.ralph-burning/`\n- `workspace.toml`\n- `active-project`\n- `projects/<project-id>/project.toml`\n- `projects/<project-id>/prompt.md`\n- `projects/<project-id>/run.json`\n- `projects/<project-id>/journal.ndjson`\n- `projects/<project-id>/sessions.json`\n- `projects/<project-id>/history/payloads/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/history/artifacts/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/logs/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/backend/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/temp/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/amendments/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/rollback/*`\n- `requirements/<requirements-run-id>/*`\n- `daemon/tasks/*`\n- `daemon/leases/*`\n\nYou must persist:\n- canonical project metadata and active run state\n- payload records and payload-derived artifacts\n- journal and runtime-log metadata/indexes\n- rollback points and amendment queue\n\n## 7) Core Invariants (MUST pass)\n- Each project has one immutable flow preset.\n- Every active run has one stage cursor.\n- Stage cursor stage must belong to the project’s selected flow.\n- Cycle and completion round numbers are monotonic and independent.\n- Structured payload validation must happen before any state mutation.\n- Domain validation must happen after schema validation, before transition commit.\n- Durable project history = journal + payloads + rendered artifacts only.\n- Runtime logs are never promoted into durable history.\n- Starting `run start` on a project with an active run must resume or fail with explicit message; it must not create duplicate active runs.\n- Resume is allowed only from durable stage boundaries.\n- Terminal state transitions persist before cleanup of external side effects when possible.\n- Explicit model overrides trump role defaults.\n- Session reuse only for roles/backends that explicitly allow it.\n- Cancellation and timeout must immediately halt retries for the run/call.\n- One writer lock per project.\n- One active daemon task per issue.\n- One worktree lease per task.\n- Command-based routing overrides label-based routing; label overrides repo default.\n- Hard rollback: logical rollback must happen before repository reset.\n- Unsupported workspace versions fail fast with no implicit migration.\n\n## 8) CLI Contract (v1 surface)\nAll commands exit non-zero on invalid state or policy failures.\n\nWorkspace/config:\n- `ralph-burning init`\n- `ralph-burning config show`\n- `ralph-burning config get <key>`\n- `ralph-burning config set <key> <value>`\n- `ralph-burning config edit`\n\nFlow discovery:\n- `ralph-burning flow list`\n- `ralph-burning flow show <flow-id>`\n\nProjects:\n- `ralph-burning project create --id <id> --name <name> --prompt <file> --flow <flow-id>`\n- `ralph-burning project select <id>`\n- `ralph-burning project list`\n- `ralph-burning project show [<id>]`\n- `ralph-burning project delete <id>`\n\nRun lifecycle:\n- `ralph-burning run start`\n- `ralph-burning run resume`\n- `ralph-burning run status`\n- `ralph-burning run history`\n- `ralph-burning run tail [--logs]`\n- `ralph-burning run rollback --to <target> [--hard]`\n\nRequirements:\n- `ralph-burning requirements draft --idea \"<text>\"`\n- `ralph-burning requirements quick --idea \"<text>\"`\n- `ralph-burning requirements show <run-id>`\n- `ralph-burning requirements answer <run-id>`\n\nDaemon:\n- `ralph-burning daemon start`\n- `ralph-burning daemon status`\n- `ralph-burning daemon abort <task-id>`\n- `ralph-burning daemon retry <task-id>`\n- `ralph-burning daemon reconcile`\n\nConformance:\n- `ralph-burning conformance list`\n- `ralph-burning conformance run [--filter <scenario-id>]`\n\nClarifications for CLI behavior:\n- `run tail` shows durable history only by default.\n- `run tail --logs` appends latest runtime logs.\n- `loop` is accepted only as a user-facing alias; `cycle` is canonical in docs and output schema.\n\n## 9) Built-in Flow Presets (v1)\nFlows are fixed per project at creation and cannot change.\nFlow stages are deterministic and configured in code:\n- `standard`: `prompt_review` (optional by config) → `planning` → `implementation` → `qa` → `review` → `completion_panel` → `acceptance_qa` → `final_review` (preset-driven)\n- `quick_dev`: `plan_and_implement` → `review` → `apply_fixes` → `final_review`\n- `docs_change`: `docs_plan` → `docs_update` → `docs_validation` → `review`\n- `ci_improvement`: `ci_plan` → `ci_update` → `ci_validation` → `review`\n\nValidation profile and final review defaults:\n- `standard`: final review enabled.\n- `quick_dev`: final review enabled, lightweight panel.\n- `docs_change`: final review disabled by default.\n- `ci_improvement`: final review disabled by default.\n\nValidation profiles include all required checks named in each preset’s default profile and may add policy-specific stricter checks when explicitly configured.\n\n## 10) Structured Stage Contracts (mandatory)\nFor every supported stage:\n- Define `StageContract` with JSON schema.\n- Persist raw backend output for diagnostics.\n- Validate payload schema first.\n- Apply semantic domain validation second.\n- Render Markdown deterministically from payload after successful validation.\n- Do not parse Markdown for state transitions.\n- Persist both payload and rendered artifact atomically under project history.\n\nRetry and failure classes must be explicit:\n- transport failure\n- schema validation failure\n- domain-validation failure\n- timeout\n- cancellation\n- qa/review outcome failure\nDifferent classes must map to distinct retry/terminal policies.\n\n## 11) Project and Run Record Rules\n`project` model stores:\n- id, name, prompt reference/hash, fixed flow, active run pointer, run state, stage cursor, cycle history, completion rounds, sessions, amendment queue, rollback points, status summary, and journal pointer.\n\nRun state transitions must never infer from artifacts.  \n`journal.ndjson` is the authoritative event source.\nState reads (`status`, `history`, `tail`) derive from canonical run/journal, not artifact scans.\n\n## 12) Agent Execution\nEvery backend invocation must produce structured stage payload-compatible output.\nEngine responsibilities:\n- parse backend spec and model spec\n- resolve per-role backend/model\n- verify backend capability for target stage contract before run start\n- check availability\n- invoke with timeout and cancellation\n- normalize to standard invocation envelope\n- preserve raw output in runtime logs\nUnsupported or mis-structured backend outputs must fail the stage with explicit class and no state transition.\n\n## 13) Automation Routing\nImplement daemon task routing with these precedence rules:\n1. explicit routing command (e.g., `/rb flow <flow-id>`)\n2. routing label (e.g., `rb:flow:<flow-id>`)\n3. repository default\n\nLabel vocabulary baseline:\n- `rb:flow:standard`\n- `rb:flow:quick_dev`\n- `rb:flow:docs_change`\n- `rb:flow:ci_improvement`\n- command and label values are validated against built-in presets only.\n\n## 14) Delivery Roadmap (Minimum v1 order)\nExecute in bounded slices with explicit handoff gates:\n\n1) Charter + v1 domain model + scenario IDs + workspace init + flow discovery.  \n2) Flow preset definitions + stage contracts + renderer contracts.  \n3) Workspace governance effective config + active project resolution.  \n4) Project/run canonical store + journal + query commands.  \n5) Agent execution facade with structured-output guarantee.  \n6) Standard preset vertical path (`run start`) end-to-end with schema/renderer persistence.  \n7) Retry/remediation, prompt review, resume, and failure class semantics.  \n8) Completion/acceptance/final-review behavior + amendment queue.  \n9) docs and CI preset integration on same engine.  \n10) Requirements drafting and project-seed handoff.  \n11) Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, interactive requirements path.  \n12) Cutover: no legacy runtime paths in v1 entrypoint; conformance gate in CI.\n\n## 15) Testability Requirements (hard constraints)\n- All public behavior is defined in Gherkin under `tests/conformance/features/`.\n- Every flow preset and routing policy has scenario coverage.\n- Conformance must include scenario filtering and fail-fast semantics (non-zero exit if any selected scenario fails).\n- For each context, implement:\n  - pure domain/unit tests for state and transition rules\n  - service-level tests with fake ports\n  - adapter contract tests\n  - targeted integration tests\n- Core invariants must have property/invariant tests where feasible.\n- Regression protection: any change to public flow behavior must update/extend corresponding scenario IDs.","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_11","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,320p' /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/010-requirements-drafting-and-project-seed-handoff/20260312193814-spec.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 10\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-12T19:38:14Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing the current rewrite workspace, loop artifacts, and git history to determine what is already implemented and what the next missing slice should be. First I’ll inspect `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and the current code/test surface so the next feature is grounded in what actually exists.\nThe workspace is the rewrite repo under `ralph-burning-rewrite/`; loop 9 is the latest completed checkpoint. I didn’t get `prompt.md` from the first pass, so I’m narrowing into the rewrite project and the loop/spec artifacts that define current scope and completed behavior.\nI’ve confirmed the planning state lives under `.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/`, with loop specs through 009 approved. Next I’m checking the actual prompt, the latest spec, and the code/test surface for `quick_dev`, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` so I can avoid proposing a slice that is already in place.\nThe shared engine is already generalized for all flow semantics, including `quick_dev`; the only hard block I’ve found there is the CLI guard that still rejects `quick_dev`. In contrast, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` are still command stubs with empty context modules, so I’m checking whether the roadmap and existing tests make `quick_dev` or `requirements drafting` the next real gap.\nThe roadmap pattern is consistent: loops 1 through 9 map directly to roadmap items 1 through 9, and there’s no loop 10 implementation in git history. I’m pulling the legacy PRD/reference materials now so the next spec can be detailed without accidentally inheriting old storage or protocol decisions.\nI found one architectural coupling that matters for the next slice: `agent_execution` currently hardcodes `workflow_composition::StageContract` and the project-flow `StageId`. Requirements drafting will need structured contracts too, so the spec needs to generalize that interface instead of smuggling requirements stages into the project workflow enum.\n# Feature: Requirements Drafting and Project Seed Handoff\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 9 already delivered the rewrite foundation: workspace init and flow discovery, stage contracts and renderers, effective config and active project resolution, canonical project/run storage and queries, agent execution, standard-flow orchestration, retry/resume semantics, completion rounds and amendments, and docs/CI flow execution. Git checkpoint history stops at loop 9 planning, and the entire `requirements` bounded context plus all four `requirements` CLI commands are still stubs at `HEAD`. The next missing roadmap slice is a canonical requirements-run workflow under `.ralph-burning/requirements/` that can draft requirements from an idea, pause for clarifying answers when needed, and emit a durable project-seed handoff without auto-creating a project or touching legacy `.ralph` PRD state.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Introduce a `RequirementsRun` state model persisted at `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/run.json` with, at minimum, `run_id`, `idea`, `mode` (`draft` or `quick`), `status` (`drafting`, `awaiting_answers`, `completed`, `failed`), `question_round`, `latest_question_set_id`, `latest_draft_id`, `latest_review_id`, `latest_seed_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, and `status_summary`.\n- [ ] Each requirements run also persists `journal.ndjson`, `answers.toml`, `answers.json`, `history/payloads/*`, `history/artifacts/*`, `seed/project.json`, `seed/prompt.md`, and `runtime/{logs,backend}/*` under `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/`.\n- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` derives its read model from `run.json` and `journal.ndjson`, not by scanning artifacts, and prints the run ID, mode, status, question round, last failure summary if present, pending question count, recommended flow, and the seed prompt path when complete.\n- [ ] Define structured contracts and deterministic renderers for four requirements-stage outputs: `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`.\n- [ ] Requirements contract validation follows the same invariant as project stages: schema validation occurs before any state mutation, domain validation occurs after schema validation and before transition commit, and rendered Markdown is never parsed for control flow.\n- [ ] `question_set` payloads include stable question IDs, prompt text, rationale, `required` flag, and optional suggested defaults; those IDs are the only keys accepted in `answers.toml` and persisted `answers.json`.\n- [ ] `requirements_draft` payloads include a problem summary, goals, non-goals, constraints, acceptance criteria, risks or open questions, and a recommended flow constrained to the built-in presets only: `standard`, `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, or `ci_improvement`.\n- [ ] `project_seed` payloads include a recommended project `id`, project `name`, built-in `flow`, a final `prompt.md` body, and a short handoff summary suitable for manual `project create --prompt`.\n- [ ] `requirements draft --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run, durably records the idea, invokes question generation, and either transitions to `awaiting_answers` after committing the question payload/artifact plus an editable `answers.toml` template, or continues directly into draft/review/seed generation when no questions are required.\n- [ ] `requirements quick --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run in `quick` mode, skips question generation entirely, and executes draft -> review -> seed generation in one command using the same persistence and validation rules.\n- [ ] `requirements answer <run-id>` is valid for runs in `awaiting_answers` and for failed runs whose latest durable boundary is a committed question set; it opens `<run-dir>/answers.toml` in `$EDITOR`, validates that every required question has a non-empty answer, persists `answers.json`, and resumes from the answers boundary instead of creating a new run.\n- [ ] If `$EDITOR` fails or exits non-zero during `requirements answer`, the run state, journal, and previously accepted answers remain unchanged.\n- [ ] Requirements drafting reuses `agent_execution`, but `agent_execution` must be generalized from workflow-only `StageContract` usage to a domain-neutral structured-contract interface so requirements contracts do not have to be added to the project workflow `StageId` enum.\n- [ ] Planner defaults drive question generation, drafting, and project-seed generation; reviewer defaults drive requirements review; existing workspace default backend/model resolution and raw-output persistence rules continue to apply.\n- [ ] Review outcomes have distinct semantics: `approved` allows seed generation and completion; `conditionally_approved` still completes but records follow-ups in canonical seed metadata and the rendered handoff summary; `request_changes` and `rejected` fail the run after the review payload/artifact are durably committed and before any seed files become visible.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the question payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the run must not transition to `awaiting_answers` and no partial question/template files may remain visible.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if answer validation fails, `answers.json` is not replaced, no draft/review/seed stage runs, and the run remains at the same committed question boundary.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the draft or review payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the corresponding journal success event is not appended and no downstream stage begins.\n- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if `seed/project.json` is written but `seed/prompt.md` fails, both seed outputs are removed, the run remains non-completed, and only the already committed draft/review history survives.\n- [ ] Completed requirements runs are immutable, failed runs retain the latest committed question set, answers, draft, and review artifacts, and `question_round` is monotonic across repeated answer cycles.\n- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` prints a suggested `ralph-burning project create --id ... --name ... --flow ... --prompt <seed/prompt.md>` command assembled from `seed/project.json` and `seed/prompt.md`.\n- [ ] This loop does not auto-create, mutate, select, or delete projects; project handoff is durable seed output only, leaving `project create` as an explicit user action.\n- [ ] Public behavior is covered by new Gherkin scenarios for: draft requiring answers, draft with no questions, quick-mode happy path, editor failure, answer validation failure, conditional approval handoff, review request_changes failure, and seed-write rollback.\n- [ ] Existing workspace, project, and run behavior remains unchanged, including the current quick_dev run-execution deferral outside the `requirements` command surface.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/mod.rs` - replace the placeholder with module exports and public entrypoints for the requirements lifecycle\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/model.rs` - add requirements run IDs, status enums, journal event types, pointers to latest payloads, and seed metadata\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/contracts.rs` - define domain-neutral contracts for `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/renderers.rs` - render deterministic `questions.md`, `requirements.md`, `review.md`, and seed handoff artifacts\n- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/service.rs` - orchestrate `draft`, `quick`, `show`, and `answer`, including answer-template validation and seed rollback rules\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/model.rs` - generalize invocation metadata away from workflow-only `StageContract` coupling\n- `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` - support domain-neutral contract evaluation while preserving existing workflow behavior\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` - adapt existing workflow stage contracts to the generalized agent-execution contract interface\n- `src/adapters/fs.rs` - add filesystem stores for requirements runs, journals, answer files, payload/artifact history, runtime diagnostics, and atomic seed-pair writes\n- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` - add deterministic requirements-stage payloads for tests\n- `src/cli/requirements.rs` - implement all four requirements commands and the editor-driven answer flow\n- `src/shared/error.rs` - add invalid requirements state, answer validation, and seed persistence error variants\n- `tests/conformance/features/requirements_drafting.feature` - add public requirements-drafting scenarios\n- `tests/unit/requirements_drafting_test.rs` - add domain and service tests for the requirements state machine and failure invariants\n- `tests/cli.rs` - add end-to-end CLI coverage for `requirements draft`, `requirements quick`, `requirements show`, and `requirements answer`\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 9 (Docs Change and CI Improvement Flow Execution)\n- Blocks: Loop 11 (Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, and interactive requirements path)\n\n---\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
